---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="How to Convert Celsius to Fahrenheit (Formula + Quick Tricks)" description="Learn the exact formula to convert Celsius to Fahrenheit and vice versa. Includes mental math shortcuts, a temperature chart, and common examples." keywords="celsius to fahrenheit, fahrenheit to celsius, temperature conversion formula, C to F, how to convert temperature">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <!-- Breadcrumb -->
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Temperature</span>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">How to Convert Celsius to Fahrenheit</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 4, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Whether you're travelling to the US, following a recipe, or just checking the weather, knowing how to convert between Celsius and Fahrenheit is a life skill. Here's everything you need.</p>

      <h2>The Formula</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">°F = (°C × 9/5) + 32</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Or equivalently: °F = (°C × 1.8) + 32</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Quick Mental Math Trick</h2>
      <p>Don't have a calculator? Use this shortcut that gets you within 1-2 degrees:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Double</strong> the Celsius number</li>
        <li><strong>Subtract 10%</strong> of that result</li>
        <li><strong>Add 32</strong></li>
      </ol>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> 25°C → 25×2 = 50 → 50−5 = 45 → 45+32 = <strong>77°F</strong> ✓</p>

      <h2>Going the Other Way: Fahrenheit to Celsius</h2>
      <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900/20 border border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-blue-700 dark:text-blue-400">°C = (°F − 32) × 5/9</p>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> 98.6°F → (98.6−32) × 5/9 = 66.6 × 0.556 = <strong>37°C</strong> (body temperature)</p>

      <h2>Common Temperatures Reference</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <thead class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
            <tr><th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Description</th><th class="px-4 py-2 text-center">°C</th><th class="px-4 py-2 text-center">°F</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Water freezes</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">0</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">32</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Cool room</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">18</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">64</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Comfortable room</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">22</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">72</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Hot day</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">35</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">95</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Body temperature</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">37</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">98.6</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Fever</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">39</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">102</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Water boils</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">100</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">212</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="px-4 py-2">Oven (moderate)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">180</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center font-mono">356</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Why Two Systems?</h2>
      <p>Celsius (also called Centigrade) is based on water: 0° = freezing, 100° = boiling. It's used by every country except the US, Liberia, and Myanmar.</p>
      <p>Fahrenheit was created earlier (1724) by Daniel Fahrenheit. In his scale, 0° was the coldest temperature he could create in a lab, and 96° was body temperature (later refined to 98.6°).</p>

      <h2>When Does It Matter?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cooking:</strong> US recipes use °F, European ones use °C</li>
        <li><strong>Weather:</strong> "It's 100°F" sounds extreme to a European (it's 38°C)</li>
        <li><strong>Medicine:</strong> A fever is 38°C / 100.4°F — know both</li>
        <li><strong>Science:</strong> Always Celsius (or Kelvin)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Try It Now</h2>
      <p>Use our <a href="/convert/temperature" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-semibold hover:underline">Temperature Converter</a> for instant, accurate conversions between Celsius, Fahrenheit, and Kelvin.</p>

      <!-- Related posts -->
      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <a href="/blog/kg-to-lbs-conversion-guide" class="block text-sm text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline">→ Kilograms to Pounds: The Complete Conversion Guide</a>
          <a href="/blog/metric-vs-imperial-which-countries" class="block text-sm text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline">→ Metric vs Imperial: Which Countries Use Which System?</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/temperature" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
